[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] As an explanatory analogy, Apache TinkerPop and Gremlin are to graph databases what the JDBC and SQL are to relational databases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Likewise, the Gremlin traversal machine is to graph computing as what the Java virtual machine is to general purpose computing.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Gremlin is an Apache2-licensed graph traversal language that can be used by graph system vendors.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] There are typically two types of graph system vendors: OLTP graph databases and OLAP graph processors.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The table below outlines those graph vendors that support Gremlin.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The following examples of Gremlin queries and responses in a Gremlin-Groovy environment are relative to a graph representation of the MovieLens dataset.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The dataset includes users who rate movies.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Users each have one occupation, and each movie has one or more categories associated with it.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The MovieLens graph schema is detailed below.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Gremlin supports declarative graph pattern matching similar to SPARQL.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] For instance, the following query below uses Gremlin's *match()*-step.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Gremlin is a virtual machine composed of an instruction set as well as an execution engine.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] An analogy is drawn between Gremlin and Java.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The following traversal is a Gremlin traversal in the Gremlin-Java8 dialect.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The Gremlin language (i.e. the fluent-style of expressing a graph traversal) can be represented in any host language that supports function composition and function nesting.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Due to this simple requirement, there exists various Gremlin dialects including Gremlin-Groovy, Gremlin-Scala, Gremlin-Clojure, etc.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The above Gremlin-Java8 traversal is ultimately compiled down to a step sequence called a *traversal*.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] A string representation of the traversal above provided below.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The *steps* are the primitives of the Gremlin graph traversal machine.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] They are the parameterized instructions that the machine ultimately executes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The Gremlin instruction set is approximately 30 steps.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] These steps are sufficient to provide general purpose computing and what is typically required to express the common motifs of any graph traversal query.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Given that Gremlin is a language, an instruction set, and a virtual machine, it is possible to design another traversal language that compiles to the Gremlin traversal machine (analogous to how Scala compiles to the JVM).
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] For instance, the popular SPARQL graph pattern match language can be compiled to execute on the Gremlin machine.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] In Gremlin-Java8, the SPARQL query above would be represented as below and compile to the identical Gremlin step sequence (i.e. traversal).
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] The Gremlin graph traversal machine can execute on a single machine or across a multi-machine compute cluster.
[src:gremlin-traversal/apache-tinkerpop] Execution agnosticism allows Gremlin to run over both graph databases (OLTP) and graph processors (OLAP).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] It is most known for creating the Neo4j Graph database, a graph database management system (GDBMS), which is implemented in Java and accessible from software written in other languages using the Cypher query language through a transactional HTTP endpoint, or through the binary "Bolt" protocol.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The company contributed to the development of the Graph Query Language (GQL), an ISO-standardized query language for property graphs, and is a founding member of the GraphQL Foundation, an open-source initiative under the Linux Foundation.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Graph database management systems, such as the Neo4j Graph Database, are used in artificial intelligence applications to represent and query relationships within connected data.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] As of 2024, the company was valued at $2.2 billion with over 800 employees and 1,700 customers globally, with deployments across financial institutions, government, retailers, and technology companies.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j has over 300 enterprise customers, including Adobe, Microsoft, Walmart, UBS, and Daimler Truck.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j is developed by Neo4j, Inc., headquartered in San Mateo, California, United States, with locations in Sweden, Germany, the United Kingdom, France, Singapore, and Australia.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The company was founded in 2007 in Sweden as an open source project by Emil Eifrem, Johan Svensson, and Peter Neubauer, but the idea for the company dates back to a drawing Eifrem sketched on the back of his napkin during a flight in 2000.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j was developed as an alternative to traditional tabular databases for use cases in which data relationships are central to the structure and querying of information.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] It is used in applications such as AI systems, recommendation engines, fraud detection, supply chain, and pharmaceutical research, where traversing relationships between data points is a requirement.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The name combines "Neo," meaning "new," with "4j," a naming convention in the Java community meaning "for Java." The project was originally called “Project Neo,” and the name Neo4j was adopted when the company was formed.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The company helped popularize the term “graph database,” thus creating a new market category.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2011, the company relocated to Silicon Valley, while its engineering hub remained in Sweden.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2016, the Neo4j graph database was used in the analysis of the Panama Papers, a data leak that exposed how wealthy individuals and organizations used offshore financial structures to manage and conceal assets.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2017, NASA acknowledged Neo4j’s contribution to Project Orion for its use in retrieving missing data from the Apollo program.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2018, the company launched its Graphs4Good program to support social impact and non-corporate use cases.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] During the COVID-19 pandemic, Neo4j supported vaccine product development.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j surpassed $200 million in revenue in 2024, and in 2025, it was reported that 84 of the Fortune 100 and over half of the Fortune 500 use Neo4j’s software to build, orchestrate, and deploy graph databases, including in AI systems at Uber, Walmart, and Daimler Truck.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2025, Neo4j announced a $100 million investment in generative AI, including a startup program supporting 1,000 AI-focused companies worldwide; program members include Medium, Shutl (acquired by eBay), and SOUQ (acquired by Amazon).
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2026, the company announced its acquisition of GraphAware, an intelligence analysis software provider for government agencies, as part of its AI investment.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j participates in the AI Alliance and engages with Linux Foundation projects focused on open-source data and AI ecosystems.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j raised $10.6 million in Series A Funding led by Fidelity Growth Partners Europe in 2011.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In November 2012, the company raised $11 million in Series B Funding led by Sunstone Capital.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In January 2015, Neo4j secured $20 million in Series C Funding led by Creandum and Dawn Capital.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In November 2016, Neo4j secured $36 million in Series D Funding led by Greenbridge Partners Ltd.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In November 2018, Neo4j secured $80 million in Series E Funding led by One Peak Partners and Morgan Stanley Expansion Capital, with participation from other investors including Creandum, Eight Roads and Greenbridge Partners.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In June 2021, Neo4j announced $325 million in Series F funding, led by Eurazeo and GV (Alphabet’s venture capital arm), which valued the company at over $2 billion making the company one of the best funded database companies.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In late 2024, the company began preparations for an initial public offering (IPO) on the Nasdaq stock exchange.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] By early 2025, the company announced it had surpassed $200 million in Annual Recurring Revenue (ARR).
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2026, the company continues to maintain its position as the most widely deployed graph database, according to industry rankings, while remaining IPO-ready as market conditions for tech listings stabilize.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j released version 1.0 of its graph database in 2010, version 2.0 in 2013, version 3.0 in 2016, version 3.5 in 2018, aimed at AI and machine learning, and version 4.0 in 2020 with unlimited scaling, partitioning, also known as ‘sharding,’ and role-based access.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2022, version 5.0 of its graph database was released.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j launched Ops Manager, a tool to monitor and manage global deployments in a unified dashboard in 2022, and vector search to its graph database in 2023, expanding contextual search for generative AI and large language models.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In 2025, the company launched agentic AI enterprise offerings; Neo4j Aura Agent lets companies build, test, and deploy AI agents using their enterprise data, providing end-to-end automated orchestration and AIOps for graph-based knowledge retrieval.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j also launched Aura Graph Analytics for cloud data warehouses and data lake platforms, including Oracle, Microsoft SQL and OneLake, Databricks, Snowflake, and Google BigQuery.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In September 2025, Neo4j introduced Infinigraph, a scalable graph database architecture designed for operational, analytical and AI workloads at over 100 terabytes and billions of nodes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In March 2024, Neo4j and Microsoft announced a collaboration to integrate graph database capabilities into Azure AI services, including Fabric and Azure OpenAI.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The integration lets users build knowledge graphs, supporting AI use cases such as GraphRAG.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] In June 2024, Neo4j integrated with Snowflake to enable graph analytics and machine learning directly within the Snowflake AI Data Cloud, allowing users access to 65 graph algorithms using SQL.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j has multiple editions for both its self-managed and fully managed offerings.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] As an ACID-compliant transactional database with native graph storage and processing, Neo4j graph database is available in three editions: Community Edition, Enterprise Edition, and Infinigraph Edition.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Community Edition is free and open source software under the GNU General Public License version 3 (GPLv3).
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The Enterprise and Infinigraph Editions are distributed under a closed-source commercial license and includes additional features related to scalability, performance, operability, and security.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The previous licensing of Enterprise Edition was dual-licensed: GPL v3 (with parts of the code under AGPLv3 with Commons Clause), allowing for clustering, hot backups, and monitoring.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j AuraDB is available in four tiers: Free, Professional, Business Critical, and Virtual Dedicated Cloud.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] The data elements Neo4j stores in its graph database are nodes, edges which connect nodes to one another, and attributes of nodes and edges.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] As of version 2.0, indexing was added to Cypher with the introduction of schemas.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Previously, indexes were supported separately from Cypher.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Database researcher Andy Pavlo from Carnegie Mellon University has questioned graph databases' decision to abandon the longstanding relational model in favor of a custom model.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Researchers from CWI benchmarked a modified version of DuckDB against Neo4j on graph-related workloads and found that, despite being an extension of a relational database running SQL, their implementation outperforms Neo4j in a few specific tasks.
[src:gremlin-traversal/neo4j] Neo4j sued PureThink, for utilizing a power created under the terms of the GNU AGPL, to remove a restrictive Commons clause that Neo4j had added to the AGPL license.
[src:gremlin-traversal/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:gremlin-traversal/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:gremlin-traversal/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:gremlin-traversal/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:gremlin-traversal/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In computing, **reactive programming** is a declarative programming paradigm concerned with data streams and the propagation of change.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] With this paradigm, it is possible to express static (e.g., arrays) or dynamic (e.g., event emitters) data streams with ease, and also communicate that an inferred dependency within the associated execution model exists, which facilitates the automatic propagation of the changed data flow.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] For example, in *imperative* programming, `a := b + c` would mean that `a` is being assigned the result of `b + c` at the time the expression is evaluated, and later, the values of `b` and `c` can be changed with no effect on the value of `a`.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In contrast, in *reactive* programming, the value of `a` is automatically updated whenever the values of `b` or `c` change, without the program having to explicitly re-state the statement `a := b + c` to re-assign the value of `a`.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Another example is a hardware description language such as Verilog, where reactive programming enables changes to be modeled as they propagate through circuits.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has been proposed as a way to simplify creating interactive user interfaces and near-real-time computing animation.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] For example, in a model–view–controller (MVC) architecture, reactive programming can facilitate changes in an underlying *model* being reflected automatically in an associated *view*.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Several popular approaches are employed in creating reactive programming languages.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] One approach is the specification of *dedicated* languages that are specific to various *domain constraints*.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Such constraints usually are characterized by real-time, embedded computing or hardware description.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Another approach involves the specification of *general-purpose* languages that include support for reactivity.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Other approaches are articulated in the definition, and use of programming *libraries*, or *embedded domain-specific languages*, that enable reactivity alongside or atop a programming language.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Specification and use of these different approaches results in language *capability trade-offs*.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In general, the more restricted a language is, the more its associated compilers and analysis programming tools are able to inform developers (e.g., in performing analysis for whether programs are able to execute in actual real-time).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Functional trade-offs in specificity may result in deterioration of the general applicability of a language.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] A variety of models and semantics govern reactive programming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive programming language runtimes are represented by a graph that identifies the dependencies among the involved reactive values.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In such a graph, *nodes* represent the act of computing, and *edges* model dependency relationships.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Such a runtime employs said graph, to help it keep track of the various computations, which must be executed anew, once an involved input changes value.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] At the implementation level, *event reaction* consists of the propagation across a graph's information, which characterizes the existence of change.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Consequently, computations that are affected by such change then become outdated and must be flagged for re-execution.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Such computations are then usually characterized by the transitive closure of the change (i.e., the full set of transitive dependencies a source affects) in its associated source.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] *Change propagation* may then lead to an update in the value of the graph's *sinks*.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Graph propagated information can consist of a node's complete state, i.e., the computation result of the involved node.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In such cases, the node's previous output is then ignored.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Another method involves *delta propagation* i.e.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In this case, information is proliferated along a graph's *edges,* which consist only of *delta*s describing how the previous node was changed.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This approach is especially important when *nodes* hold large amounts of *state data*, which would otherwise be expensive to recompute from scratch.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Another common optimization is employment of *unary change accumulation* and *batch propagation*.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Such a solution can be faster because it reduces communication among involved nodes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Optimization strategies can then be employed that reason about the nature of the changes contained within, and make alterations accordingly (e.g. two changes in the batch can cancel each other, and thus, simply be ignored).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Yet another available approach, is described as *invalidity notification propagation*.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This approach causes nodes with invalid input to pull updates, thus resulting in the update of their own outputs.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] A graph of dependencies is program-specific and generated by a programmer.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] When propagating changes, it is possible to pick propagation orders such that the value of an expression is not a natural consequence of the source program.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] We can illustrate this easily with an example.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Suppose `seconds` is a reactive value that changes every second to represent the current time (in seconds).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Because `t` should always be greater than `seconds`, this expression should always evaluate to a true value.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Unfortunately, this can depend on the order of evaluation.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] When `seconds` changes, two expressions have to update: `seconds + 1` and the conditional.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] If the first evaluates before the second, then this invariant will hold.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] If, however, the conditional updates first, using the old value of `t` and the new value of `seconds`, then the expression will evaluate to a false value.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Some reactive languages are glitch-free and prove this property.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This is usually achieved by topologically sorting expressions and updating values in topological order.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This can, however, have performance implications, such as delaying the delivery of values (due to the order of propagation).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Topological sorting of dependencies depends on the dependency graph being a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In practice, a program may define a dependency graph that has cycles.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Usually, reactive programming languages expect such cycles to be "broken" by placing some element along a "back edge" to permit reactive updating to terminate.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Typically, languages provide an operator like `delay` that is used by the update mechanism for this purpose, since a `delay` implies that what follows must be evaluated in the "next time step" (allowing the current evaluation to terminate).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive languages typically assume that their expressions are purely functional.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This allows an update mechanism to choose different orders in which to perform updates, and leave the specific order unspecified (thereby enabling optimizations).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] When a reactive language is embedded in a programming language with state, however, it may be possible for programmers to perform mutable operations.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] How to make this interaction smooth remains an open problem.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In some cases, it is possible to have principled partial solutions.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In some reactive languages, the graph of dependencies is *static*, i.e., the graph is fixed throughout a program's execution.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In other languages, the graph can be *dynamic*, i.e., it can change as the program executes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Every second, the value of this expression changes to a different reactive expression, which `t + 1` then depends on.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Therefore, the graph of dependencies updates every second.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Permitting dynamic updating of dependencies provides significant expressive power (for instance, dynamic dependencies routinely occur in graphical user interface (GUI) programs).
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] However, the reactive update engine must decide whether to reconstruct expressions each time, or to keep an expression's node constructed but inactive; in the latter case, ensure that they do not participate in the computation when they are not supposed to be active.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive programming languages can range from very explicit ones where data flows are set up by using arrows, to implicit where the data flows are derived from language constructs that look similar to those of imperative or functional programming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] For example, in an implicitly lifted functional reactive programming (FRP), a function call might implicitly cause a node in a data flow graph to be constructed.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive programming libraries for dynamic languages (such as the Lisp "Cells" and Python "Trellis" libraries) can construct a dependency graph from runtime analysis of the values read during a function's execution, allowing data flow specifications to be both implicit and dynamic.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Sometimes the term *reactive programming* refers to the architectural level of software engineering, where individual nodes in the data flow graph are ordinary programs that communicate with each other.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive programming can be purely static where the data flows are set up statically, or be dynamic where the data flows can change during the execution of a program.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] The use of data switches in the data flow graph could to some extent make a static data flow graph appear as dynamic, and blur the distinction slightly.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] True dynamic reactive programming however could use imperative programming to reconstruct the data flow graph.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive programming could be said to be of **higher order** if it supports the idea that data flows could be used to construct other data flows.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] That is, the resulting value out of a data flow is another data flow graph that is executed using the same evaluation model as the first.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Ideally all data changes are propagated instantly, but this cannot be assured in practice.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Instead, it might be necessary to give different parts of the data flow graph different evaluation priorities.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This can be called **differentiated reactive programming**.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] For example, in a word processor, marking spelling errors need not be synchronized fully with adding or inserting characters.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Here, differentiated reactive programming can be used to give a spell checker lower priority, allowing it to be delayed while keeping other data flows more immediate.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] However, such differentiation introduces added design complexity.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] For example, deciding how to define the different data flow areas, and how to handle event passing between different data flow areas.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Evaluation of reactive programs is not necessarily based on how stack-based programming languages are evaluated.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Instead, when some data is changed, the change is propagated to all data that is derived partially or completely from the data that was changed.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This change propagation could be achieved in a number of ways, where perhaps the most natural way is an invalidate/lazy-revalidate scheme.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] It could be problematic simply to naively propagate a change using a stack, because of potential exponential update complexity if the data structure has a certain shape.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] One such shape can be described as "repeated diamonds shape", and has the following structure: An→Bn→An+1, An→Cn→An+1, where n=1,2...
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This problem could be overcome by propagating invalidation only when some data is not already invalidated, and later re-validate the data when needed using lazy evaluation.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] One inherent problem for reactive programming is that most computations that would be evaluated and forgotten in a normal programming language, needs to be represented in the memory as data-structures.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] This could potentially make reactive programming highly memory consuming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] However, research on what is called *lowering* could potentially overcome this problem.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] On the other side, reactive programming is a form of what could be described as "explicit parallelism", and could therefore be beneficial for using the power of parallel hardware.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Reactive programming has principal similarities with the observer pattern commonly used in object-oriented programming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] However, integrating the data flow concepts into the programming language would make it easier to express them and could therefore increase the granularity of the data flow graph.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] For example, the observer pattern commonly describes data flows between whole objects/classes, whereas object-oriented reactive programming could target the members of objects/classes.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] It is possible to fuse reactive programming with ordinary imperative programming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] In such a paradigm, imperative programs operate upon reactive data structures.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Such a set-up is analogous to imperative constraint programming; however, while imperative constraint programming manages bidirectional data-flow constraints, imperative reactive programming manages one-way data-flow constraints.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] One reference implementation is the proposed Quantum runtime extension to JavaScript.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Object-oriented reactive programming (OORP) is a combination of object-oriented programming and reactive programming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Perhaps the most natural way to make such a combination is this: instead of methods and fields, objects have *reactions* that automatically re-evaluate when the other reactions they depend on have been modified.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] If an OORP language maintains its imperative methods, it would also fall under the category of imperative reactive programming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Functional reactive programming (FRP) is a programming paradigm for reactive programming on functional programming.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] The actor model (actors) is proposed to design reactive systems, often combined with functional reactive programming (FRP) and Reactive Streams to develop distributed reactive systems.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] A newer category of programming languages uses constraints (rules) as main programming concept.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] It consists of reactions to events, which keep all constraints satisfied.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] Not only does this facilitate event-based reactions, but it makes reactive programs instrumental to the correctness of software.
[src:gremlin-traversal/reactive-programming] An example of a rule based reactive programming language is Ampersand, which is founded in relation algebra.
